align=left class=m><span class=title> Copyright</span><hr size=1> Ok, this has been confusing. When you create a work, is it automatically copyrighted, and what are the copyright specifics? And can you copyright a character without spending much money? <p><font size="1">
<HR><center><a href="http://pub92.ezboard.com/bherosreality"><img src="http://www.pcshelp.com/quest/realm/hero'sreality-minibanner.jpg"></a>      <a href="http://www.geocities.com/triforce_realm7">Triforce Realm</a></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/upixienim.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Pixie Nim</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/5/02 7:05:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4337.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://enchantedrealm.dhs.org/avatars/Cloked-Farie.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Copyright</span><hr size=1> No, it isn't automatically copyrighted just cause you drew it. However, if you date it, or if you ink and colour a picture and then find someone else is claiming it's theirs, if you can produce a dated pencil copy that'll help prove it's yours. That will probably only convince other artists, tho, it's not legally binding.<br>
<br>
One way of copyrighting artwork without spending much money is to get a copy of whatever you drew, and before you put it online (or anywhere really) stick it in an envelope and mail it to yourself. When you get it back, don't open it, stick it in a draw unopened. That way if it ever got to court, you could pretty much prove it was yours.<br>
<br>
To be honest, I'd never bother copyrighting anything I did unless I intended to become a professional illustrator or if I had a lot of problems with people theiving stuff... otherwise it's a lot of hassle for not much reward.<br>
<br>
Also, if it's people pinching your ideas (original character designs, orginal plot ideas, etc) that you're worried about, I advise you not to post your most vaulable ideas in a popular and crowded forum like this - you'll find once a new idea comes up, there'll be a rash of similar drawings appearing very shortly. I've noticed quite a few pictures of a girl in classical armour with crosses on it recently.... not my idea, by it's a good example of the sort of thing which goes on around here....<br>
<br>
<br>
